            "sidecar_changes": {
                "TaskName": "MIST1",
                "TaskDescription": "The Montreal Imaging Stress Test (MIST) is a neuroimaging psychosocial stress paradigm (Dedovic et al., 2005) with alternating control (~61s) and stress (~90s) conditions, starting with control. Each ~5-minute run repeats this sequence twice across three runs. Outside the MR scanner, participants complete a training session with control tasks. In stress conditions, they face time pressure, social evaluation via feedback (TIME OUT, WRONG, CORRECT), and performance comparisons to a fictional group. Negative comments between runs are used to increase stress, though feedback is adjusted if signs of distress (e.g., trembling voice, breath-holding) appear. For adults, tasks are set to high difficulty and low speed, with minor timing variations. For children/adolescents (Project IRTG01), the hardest level (“Level 3”) is used unless accuracy falls below 50% during the training session, prompting a reduction.",
                "Instructions": "We are testing cognitive performance in relation to hormones using math tasks in the scanner. There are two conditions: control and experimental. In the experimental condition, a blue bar shows your time limit, and your performance is compared to a control group. Use your index and ring fingers to enter answers, your middle finger to confirm. The screen will show if you are correct. Stay still and silent. Now, we’ll practice without time limits or recording.",
                "B0FieldSource": [
                    "phasediff_fmap_MIST",
                    "pepolar_fmap0_MIST"
                ]
            }
        },
